HEADWORD: Nit
<hw>Nit</hw> <pr>(n⟦icr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>hnitu</ets>; akin to D. <ets>neet</ets>, G. <ets>niss</ets>, OHG.
<ets>niz</ets>; cf. Gr. <grk>koni`s</grk>, <grk>koni`dos</grk>, Icel.
<ets>gnit</ets>, Sw. <ets>gnet</ets>, Dan. <ets>gnid</ets>, Russ. & Pol.
<ets>gnida</ets>, Bohem. <ets>hnida</ets>, W. <ets>nedd</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The egg of a louse or other small
insect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nit grass</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a pretty
annual European grass (<spn>Gastridium lendigerum</spn>), with small
spikelets somewhat resembling a nit. It is also found in California and
Chile.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nitency</ent>⟦br⟧
